AUDIO: 'not close it or something like this. But you see&nbsp; everything worked. Basically, we have it now here. All right guys, and to import your own mesh is&nbsp; also really easy. So, what you need to do is you&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'go to use your model and then what you can do&nbsp; is either upload here reference model like one&nbsp;&nbsp; of those options that I just showed you before or&nbsp; we\'re going to upload here our mesh. And as you&nbsp;&nbsp; can see, it\'s saying here Gab and FBX preferred.&nbsp; But I got to be honest with you, in my test,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it was always better to use GAB than FBX because&nbsp; with FBX, it created for me at least like an issue&nbsp;&nbsp; where it created completely new UVs and then I&nbsp; couldn\'t attach my material anymore in Blender.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So I\'m going to choose GAB because then it will&nbsp; directly also keep the material and we have it&nbsp;&nbsp; interactive kind of in our viewport playing which&nbsp; is really cool. So I\'m going to show you this now&nbsp;&nbsp; because as I mentioned I created the model here&nbsp; in tripo then I exported this as a gab and in&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'case you\'re using tredders 2 pix 3D and confi it&nbsp; will be directly a gab file so you won\'t have any&nbsp;&nbsp; problems with that. So basically what you can&nbsp; do then is simply hit upload then I\'m going to&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'import my model and then you will see it will&nbsp; directly import our character with the material&nbsp;&nbsp; attached which is really cool. So we can now auto&nbsp; align it to the floor and then you know change&nbsp;&nbsp; the orientation so that it\'s basically facing the&nbsp; front because you will see when I select here the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'skeleton template and choose here human because&nbsp; obviously this is what we need. You will see that&nbsp;&nbsp; the orientation is like this. So basically we&nbsp; would then align it to the orientation we had&nbsp;&nbsp; here. So in case your model is in a different&nbsp; orientation or like this then you can fix that&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'easily you know by going in here selected then&nbsp; in the correct position and then you have it like&nbsp;&nbsp; this. You will also notice that here the skeleton&nbsp; is larger than our model which is also no problem&nbsp;&nbsp; because we can change here the scale of our skele.&nbsp; So just make sure that it\'s roughly in the scale&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we need. So something like this could already&nbsp; work kind of like from a 50% scale maybe a bit&nbsp;&nbsp; smaller. I think 51 already matches quite well.&nbsp; So that\'s nice. And then we can also, you know,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'move our character a bit to match it a bit better&nbsp; and aligning with the rig, which is nice. So we&nbsp;&nbsp; going here to addit skeleton. And you can, by the&nbsp; way, also always go back in time when you would&nbsp;&nbsp; like to readjust things. Always go here back and&nbsp; then you can redo things and fix things in case&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you need that. So what we can do now and you might&nbsp; remember this from mixer mode basically is that we&nbsp;&nbsp; now place our control points here basically which&nbsp; are then deciding where the bones will be placed.&nbsp;&nbsp; So we can just grab a handleer here and then we&nbsp; can place them however we would like to have them.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So we can then you know place them in space so&nbsp; that they are roughly matching. You will also see&nbsp;&nbsp; that here on the top right we have this reference&nbsp; image that you can make larger and then see where&nbsp;&nbsp; the points should be placed. And you will also&nbsp; notice that we have symmetry over here. So we&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'only need to place them correctly for the right&nbsp; side and it will be then directly mirrored over to&nbsp;&nbsp; the left side which is of course also great. You&nbsp; can of course disable this as well here when you&nbsp;&nbsp; disable the checkbox over here and then you can&nbsp; place it yourself in case you like to or in case&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[09:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your model is not completely symmetrical and you&nbsp; will see that you always have a live interaction&nbsp;&nbsp; of you know when you place it higher or not of the&nbsp; weight painting we have currently which is cool.&nbsp;&nbsp; In case you would like to change your view, you&nbsp; can also do that by going to the textured view.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[09:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And then we have our mesh here again, you&nbsp; know, with our material applied basically.&nbsp;&nbsp; So I\'m going back to meshes. The most trickiest&nbsp; part is always placing the hands correctly. So,&nbsp;&nbsp; you know, we can also adjust this here a bit&nbsp; more. Always check it from all sides because&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[09:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basically when I now put it here on the right&nbsp; side, it might happen, you know, that it\'s&nbsp;&nbsp; switching then over a little bit too much on&nbsp; the far right position and we don\'t want that.&nbsp;&nbsp; And then once we have placed all bones, I would&nbsp; then go here to finish. And then as you can see,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[09:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
